<font color="#FF0000">HELICOPTERS</font><br>
<tt>Fri Oct 17  2:51:54 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To all vets,<br><br>
     I've been following along with debate/discussion on the helicopter war and had a few things I think should be said.<br><br>
No doubt that anyone who was in Vietnam, has the deepest respect for the men who flew the helicopters (I sure beers are always on the house).  Even us non-Vietnam vets can look up when they see or hear a helicopter and a part of us, heart and soul goes up there in envy with the men who live out part of the human dream to fly.  My father, a Nam vet, has the special gift of hearing, military helicopters, miles away, while he is indoors or outdoors, even before anybody else does, &quot;That's a military helicopter, you can tell by the sound!&quot; he says.<br><br>
I have always had the deepest respect for those who flew helicopters.  It takes a special breed of &quot;tough guys&quot; to do it, remember helicopters don't fly, &quot;they beat the air into submission!!&quot;  At risk of inflating egos (THEY DESERVE THE PAT ON THE BACK), I have some Vietnam helicopter facts to share for us ground pounders.<br><br>
First of all though, &quot;Why would the military have anyone over enemy airspace that they would be willing any number of men to get them out?&quot;  I think it is because helicopter crews and para-rescue men have a special devotion to duty.  It's there job to save lives, no matter where or who.  They are one determined bunch of guys, no matter what the casualties.  No one would like to be lost, wounded and left behind, and I think helicopter pilots understand the necessity of saving lives.  Just think, what kind of person does it take to stake his own life for the rescue of just one other?  A brave soul indeed.  They do it because the other guy would try to save them, its the &quot;brotherhood&quot; of combat and human survival.<br><br>
Anyway here the facts and figures. They are testimony of helicopter crew efforts in Vietnam.<br><br>
2,094 helicopter pilots of all bramches were killed in Nam.<br>
That's 1,827 from the Army, 197 from the Marines, 39 from the Air Force, 30 from the Navy and 1 from the Coast Guard.<br><br>
96 helicopter pilots are MIA.  That's 86 from the Army, 5 from the Marines, and 5 from the Navy.<br><br>
The average age of a helicopter pilot that was a casualty was 25.6 years.<br><br>
The average tour length before death was 170 days.  The first helicopter pilot to get killed was WO1 Edgar Wilken Weitkamp Jr on 23 March 1961.  The last was 2LT Richard Vande Geer, a member of the 21 Special Operations Squadron and a co-pilot of Helicopter Knife-31 that while flying a load of Marines int Koh Tang Island during the Mayaguez incident on May 15, 1975 had his helicopter hit rocket rounds that caused it to crash in the surf.  He died at his post, strapped to his seat, when the fire prevented a Marine from pulling him out.<br><br>
A total of 36,145 helicopter sorties were flown in Nam (3,952 were attack sorties, 7,547 were assaualt sorties,3,548 were cargo sorties and 21,098 were classified as other sorties) and 4,642 helicopters lost (many were recovered and repaired).<br><br>
There  legacy is one that a war like Vietnam couldn't have been conducted for as long as it did without the air-lift capability for troop movement, air resuce, and medivac flights.<br><br>
The Army alone medivaced 400,000 soldiers and countless more civilians.  The helicopter was responsible (along with great medical care) for making the it possible for 81% of those wounded in battle to survive.  The hospital mortality rate in Vietnam was 2.6% as compared to the 4.5%  in World War II and the 2.5% in Korea.  As the book MEDICAL SUPPORT OF THE US ARMY IN VIETNAM states, &quot;The very slight increase in hospital mortality in Vietnam over that in Korea was a result of rapid helicopter evacuation which brought into the hospital mortally wounded patients who, with earlier, slower means of evacuation would have died en route and would have beem recorded as KIA.  Assuming that most of those patients who died within the first 24 hours in hospitals belonged in this class, the rate would be closer to 1%&quot; (hospital mortality of wounded rate).  It is a great honor to the medical personnel and the helicopter pilots and crews that so many of the wounded survived.  Wounded men were brought in so quick that men with all kinds of wounds, even mortal made it to a hospital alive.  That's great care!!<br>
&quot;So that others may live&quot;, helicopter crews carried armies, hauled sick and wounded Vietnamese civilians to hospital, carried the American and allied wounded to QUICK hospital care, rescued lost or trapped personnel, pulled off a brave POW raid in the heart of North Vietnam at Son Tay and countless other deeds.  Thier own actions pay the greatest tribute to them.<br><br>
Of the POW/MIA bracelets I wear on a daily basis is one Navy man lost in helicopter crash and one Marine helicopter crewman whose helicopter just disappeared, shot down by the enemy.   I feel it a honor to pay tribute to those men and many others living and dead.<br><br>

